<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOTHERS' TREATMENT PROGRAM GETS GRANT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JACK SEARLES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Ventura County Health Care Agency has received a $1.8-million federal grant 
to establish a counseling and treatment program for chemically dependent 
pregnant women and recent mothers. 
</P>
<P>
The five-year grant from the Health and Human Services Department will pay for 
day care and live-in treatment for 20 women and their children at a time, said 
Stephen Kaplan, director of the county's alcohol and drug programs. 
</P>
<P>
He said as many as six of the women and their children will live in a safe 
house as part of the program. The rest of those in the program will continue to 
live at home. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a major thrust for our agency and the county," Kaplan said. "Everybody 
is concerned about chemically dependent women at childbearing age. 
</P>
<P>
"This will be the county's first attempt to pull all the necessary components 
together to work with these people from a health-care perspective." 
</P>
<P>
Kaplan said the county is negotiating a lease for the program's day-treatment 
facility. A location has not yet been chosen for the live-in shelter, he added. 
JACK SEARLES 
</P>
</TEXT>
