<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: CRUSTACEANS FORCE CLOSURE OF RESERVOIR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Small crustaceans have made their way into the drinking water supply of a 
neighborhood southwest of downtown, prompting the closure Thursday of Rowena 
Reservoir in Silver Lake for at least a month, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
It was the second time in eight days that the Department of Water and Power has 
been forced to temporarily close a reservoir in the same area because of an 
infestation believed to have been triggered by a prolonged hot spell this 
summer and the proliferation of algae, DWP spokeswoman Debra Sass said. 
</P>
<P>
On July 16, the agency closed the 77-acre Silver Lake Reservoir after residents 
in the 2900 block of Van Buren Place reported tiny brown wormlike midge fly 
larvae in their drinking water, Sass said. 
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the DWP closed the 5.7-acre Rowena Reservoir after 
translucent-yellow aquatic amphipods measuring slightly larger than a half-inch 
were discovered in the water supply for the same neighborhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
