<P>
SUSPECT JAILED IN DISCO BOMBING THAT LED TO RETALIATION ON LIBYA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WEST BERLIN 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A West German man of Arab origin has been arrested on charges of organizing the 
1986 discotheque bombing that led then-President Ronald Reagan to bomb Libya, 
authorities announced today. 
</P>
<P>
The 32-year-old suspect was seized at his home on a warrant accusing him of 
"preparing and organizing the attack on the La Belle discotheque." 
</P>
<P>
Reagan blamed Libya for the attack, in which two American servicemen and a 
Turkish woman died, and he sent U.S. planes to bomb Tripoli in retaliation. 
</P>
<P>
West Berlin Justice Department spokesman Cornel Christoffel said the man, who 
denied involvement in the bombing, was arrested when investigators searched six 
apartments in West Berlin and a cell in the city's Tegel prison. 
</P>
<P>
"The other five suspects are on the run," he added. 
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people, including many off-duty soldiers, were wounded in the La 
Belle bombing, which U.S. intelligence sources said was ordered by the Libyan 
Embassy in East Berlin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
