<HEADLINE>
<P>
STATE; 
</P>
<P>
STATE BUDGET ACCORD REACHED; $800 MILLION IN TAX, FEE HIKES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Gov. George Deukmejian and leaders of the Legislature, capping a record 27-day 
impasse, announced today that they have reached agreement on a state budget for 
the fiscal year that began July 1. 
</P>
<P>
The budget includes nearly $800 million in tax and fee increases, contains a 
variety of cuts and curtails some automatic cost-of-living increases, they 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The $50-billion-plus budget includes an automatic "trigger" sought by 
Deukmejian -- a mechanism that will automatically limit spending each year if 
there is an unexpected decline in revenues. 
</P>
<P>
The state has gone nearly a month into the new fiscal year without a budget, 
the longest period in the state's history without a spending plan. 
</P>
<P>
The hangup was caused by lawmakers' inability to agree on how best to cover a 
$3.6 billion revenue shortfall. 
</P>
<P>
"Now, we've got this proposal to present to the legislators. Hopefully, they 
will pass it as quickly as possible," Deukmejian said. But, he added, "it's 
always hard to get a two-thirds vote (in the Legislature)." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
